what is git and github
Git is a version control system that tracks changes in code, while GitHub is a cloud-based platform built on Git that allows developers to store, share, and collaborate on repositories online. In short: Git manages your code history locally, and GitHub makes it easy to collaborate globally.

🔑 Key Differences Between Git and GitHub
Feature	Git	GitHub
Type	Distributed version control system	Cloud-based hosting & collaboration platform
Where it runs	Installed locally on your computer	Hosted online (web + cloud)
Main purpose	Track changes, manage branches, merge code	Share repositories, collaborate, review code
Interface	Primarily command-line (CLI), optional GUIs	Web interface + Git integration
Collaboration	Developers work independently with full repo copies	Teams collaborate via pull requests, issues, discussions
Examples of use	git commit, git branch, git merge	Forking repos, opening pull requests, managing projects


🛠️ What Git Does
Tracks changes: Every edit you make is recorded as a "commit."

Branching & merging: Developers can experiment in separate branches and later merge changes.

Works offline: You don’t need internet access to use Git—it runs locally.

Decentralized: Each developer has a complete copy of the repository.

🌐 What GitHub Adds
Remote storage: Hosts repositories online so teams can access them anywhere.

Collaboration tools: Pull requests, code reviews, and issue tracking.

Community & open source: Millions of public repositories to learn from or contribute to.

Integrations: Works with CI/CD pipelines, project boards, and third-party apps.

⚡ How They Work Together
You use Git locally to manage your code history.

You push your repository to GitHub to share it online.

Other developers can clone, contribute, and propose changes via pull requests.

GitHub keeps everything organized and visible for the team.

✅ Practical Example
You’re building a website.

With Git, you commit changes like “added homepage layout.”

With GitHub, you upload the repo so your teammates can review and suggest improvements.

Would you like me to show you a step-by-step beginner workflow (like how to create a repo, commit, and push to GitHub)? That way, you’ll see exactly how Git and GitHub connect in practice.

Yes
Perfect! Let’s walk through a beginner-friendly Git + GitHub workflow step by step so you can see how they connect in practice:

🚀 Step-by-Step Beginner Workflow
1. Install Git
Download Git from git-scm.com.

After installation, check with:

bash
git --version
2. Set Up Git (first time only)
Configure your identity:

bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"
3. Create a Local Repository
Navigate to your project folder:

bash
cd my-project
Initialize Git:

bash
git init
4. Make Your First Commit
Add files to staging:

bash
git add .
Commit changes:

bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"
5. Create a GitHub Repository
Go to GitHub and click New Repository.

Give it a name (e.g., my-project).

6. Connect Local Repo to GitHub
Copy the GitHub repo URL.

Link your local repo:

bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/my-project.git
7. Push Code to GitHub
Upload your commits:

bash
git push -u origin main
8. Collaborate
Teammates can clone your repo:

bash
git clone https://github.com/username/my-project.git
They make changes, then open pull requests on GitHub for you to review.

🔄 Summary
Git = Tracks changes locally.

GitHub = Shares repos online for collaboration.

Together, they let you build projects, track history, and work with others seamlessly.

