# 🛠️ Contribution Guide

Welcome to the **GitHub Open Source Starter Pack Contribution Guide**!  
This document explains how you can contribute to this repository or any open-source project using Git and GitHub.

---

## 🚀 Step 1: Fork the Repository
- On GitHub, click the **Fork** button at the top right of the repo page.
- This creates a personal copy of the repository under your account.

---

## 📂 Step 2: Clone Your Fork
Download your fork to your local machine:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/GitHub-open-source-starter-pack.git
cd GitHub-open-source-starter-pack
🌱 Step 3: Create a Branch
Always work on a separate branch for your changes:

bash
git checkout -b feature-name
Example:

bash
git checkout -b add-cheatsheet
✍️ Step 4: Make Changes
Edit files, add new content, or fix issues.

Stage and commit your changes:

git add .
git commit -m "Added new cheat sheet section"

☁️ Step 5: Push Changes to Your Fork
Upload your branch to GitHub:
git push origin feature-name

🔄 Step 6: Open a Pull Request (PR)

Go to your fork on GitHub.

Click Compare & Pull Request.

Write a clear description of your changes.

Submit the PR to the original repository.
✅ Step 7: Review & Merge
Maintainers will review your PR.

They may request changes or approve and merge it.

Once merged, your contribution becomes part of the project!

💡 Tips for Contributors
Keep commits small and focused.

Write descriptive commit messages.

Follow repository guidelines and coding standards.

Be respectful and collaborative in discussions.
